    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Violence in the Park: How Did It Happen?</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>David Kearns letter recounts how he and girlfriend saw chaotic mobs of young men roving along south end of Central Park after New York's Puerto Rican Day parade, dousing people with water and passing around liquor, all with no police officer in sight (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''35 Scary Minutes: Women Tell Police of Assaults in Park''  (front page, June 13):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''35 Scary Minutes: Women Tell Police of Assaults in Park''  (front page, June 13):</p>
        <p>My girlfriend and I were sightseeing in New York City last weekend, and as we were walking to our friend's apartment on the East Side after getting out at the Columbus Circle subway station, we were confronted by a scene of complete chaos at the south end of Central Park.  Mobs of young men armed with water guns roved the area shouting and dousing people with water, shots of liquor were being openly passed among the crowd, and most disconcerting of all, there was not a police officer in sight.</p>
        <p>Hoping to avoid trouble, we decided to take a circuitous route back through the park. Ten to 15 minutes later, we saw police cars with lights flashing going toward where we had come from. After reading about the assaults that occurred, we thanked our lucky stars that we had decided to circumvent the mob scene.</p>
        <p>DAVID KEARNS  Washington, June 13, 2000</p>
      </block>
